at (1949 film)|Barsaat]]\n|-\n|[[Shakila (actress)|Shakila]]\n|Duniya\n|-\n|[[Shammi (actress)|Shammi]]\n|Ustad Pedro\n|-\n|}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n==1950s==\n<!-- When adding column entries, remember to update the rowspan count. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year with<br>lead role\n! Name \n! Debut as<br>lead role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|1952\n|[[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nadira_(actress)|Nadira]]\n|[[Aan]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1954\n|[[Shyama]]\n|[[Aar Paar]]\n|-\n|[[Ameeta]]\n|[[Shri Chaitanya Mahaprabhu (film)|Shri Chaitanya Mahaprabhu]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|1956\n|[[Waheeda Rehman]]\n|[[C.I.D. (1956 film)|C.I.D.]]\n|-\n|[[Helen (actress)|Helen]]\n|[[Halaku (film)|Halaku]]\n|-\n|1959\n|[[Minoo Mumtaz]]\n|Black Cat\n|-\n|}\n\n==1960s==\n<!-- When adding column entries, remember to update the rowspan count. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year with<br>lead role\n! Name \n! Debut as<br>lead role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1961\n|[[Saira Banu]]\n|[[Junglee (1961 film)|Junglee]]\n|-\n|[[Mumtaz (actress)|Mumtaz]]\n|[[Stree (1961 film)|Stree]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\"|1964\n|[[Sharmila Tagore]]\n|[[Kashmir Ki Kali]]\n|-\n|}\n==1970s==\n<!-- When adding column entries, remember to update the rowspan count. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year \n! Name \n! Debut film\n! Notable films\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |1971\n|[[Farida Jalal]]\n|''Laal Patthar''\n|''[[Henna (film)|Henna]]'' (1991), ''[[Mammo]]'' (1994), ''[[Dilwale Dulhania Le Jayenge]]'' (1995)\n|-\n||[[Zeenat Aman]]\n|''[[Hare Rama Hare Krishna (1971 film)|Hare Rama Hare Krishna]]''\n|''[[Yaadon Ki Baaraat]]'' (1973), ''[[Satyam Shivam Sundaram]]'' (1979), ''[[Insaaf Ka Tarazu]]'' (1980)\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" |1973\n|[[Parveen Babi]]\n|''Charitra''\n|''[[Majboor (1974 film)|Majboor]]'' (1974), ''[[Amar Akbar Anthony]]'' (1977), ''[[Namak Halaal]]'' (1982)\n|-\n|1974\n|[[Shabana Azmi]]\n|''[[Ankur (film)|Ankur]]''\n|''[[Masoom (1983 film)|Masoom]]'' (1983), ''[[Khandhar]]'' (1984), ''[[Godmother (film)|Godmother]]'' (1999)\n|-\n|1976\n|[[Reena Roy]]\n|[[Nagin (1976 film)|Naagin]]\n|\n|}\n==1980s==\n<!-- When adding column entries, remember to update the rowspan count. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Name \n! Debut film\n!Notable films\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |1983\n|[[Amrita Singh]]\n|''[[Betaab]]''\n|''[[Mard (1985 film)|Mard]]'' (1985), ''[[Naam (1986 film)|Naam]]'' (1986), ''[[Aaina (1993 film)|Aaina]]'' (1993)\n|-\n|1985\n|[[Mandakini (actress)|Mandakini]]\n|[[Ram Teri Ganga Maili]]\n|''[[Jeeva (1986 film)|Jeeva]]'' (1986), ''[[Loha (1987 film)|Loha]]'' (1987), ''[[Taqdeer Ka Tamasha]]'' (1990)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |1986\n|[[Farha Naaz]]\n|''[[Naseeb Apna Apna (1986 film)|Naseeb Apna Apna]]''\n|''[[Love 86]]'' (1986), ''[[Woh Phir Aayegi]]'' (1988), ''[[Begunaah]]'' (1991)\n|-\n|}\n==1990s==\n<!-- When adding column entries, remember to update the rowspan count. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year \n! Name \n! Debut film\n! Notable films\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |1994\n|[[Tabu (actress)|Tabu]]\n|''[[Vijaypath]]''\n|''[[Maachis]]'' (1996), ''[[Chandni Bar]]'' (2001), ''[[Cheeni Kum]]'' (2007)\n|-\n|}\n==2000s==\n<!-- When adding column entries, remember to update the rowspan count. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year with<br>lead role\n! Name \n! Debut as<br>lead role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |2000\n|[[Kareena Kapoor]]\n|[[Refugee (2000 film)|Refugee]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |2001\n|[[Dia Mirza]]\n|[[Rehna Hai Tere Dil Mein]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |2003\n|[[Katrina Kaif]]\n|[[Boom (film)|Boom]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2004\n|[[Soha Ali Khan]]\n|[[Dil Maange More|Dil Maange More!!!]]\n|-\n|[[Ayesha Takia]] \n|[[Taarzan: The Wonder Car]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |2007\n|[[Seema Azmi]]\n|[[Chak De! India]]\n|-\n|}\n==2010s==\n<!-- When adding column entries, remember to update the rowspan count. -->\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year with<br>lead role\n! Name \n! Debut as<br>lead role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2010\n|[[Zareen Khan]]\n|[[Veer (2010 film)|Veer]]\n|-\n|[[Sara Loren]]\n|[[Kajraare]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2011\n|[[Nushrat Bharucha]]\n|[[Pyaar Ka Punchnama]]\n|-\n|[[Nargis Fakhri]]\n|[[Rockstar (2011 film)|Rockstar]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" |2012\n|[[Huma Qureshi (actress)|Huma Qureshi]]\n|[[Gangs of Wasseypur \u2013 Part 1]]\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2016\n|[[Fatima Sana Shaikh]]\n|[[Dangal]]\n|-\n|[[Zaira Wasim]]\n|[[Dangal]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" |2017\n|[[Mahira Khan]] \n|[[Raees (film)|Raees]] \n|-\n|[[Saba Qamar]] \n|[[Hindi Medium]] \n|-\n| rowspan=\"1\" | 2018\n|[[Sara Ali Khan]]\n|[[Kedarnath (film)|Kedarnath]]\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\" | 2020\n|[[Hina Khan]]\n|[[Hacked]] \n|-\n|}\n", "name_user": "Shmmon", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1950s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Bollywood_Muslim_Actresses"}
{"title_page": "Religion in the United Arab Emirates", "text_new": "{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in the United Arab Emirates (2005 census)<ref name=religiousfreedom>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2010/148850.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101123103428/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2010/148850.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-11-23|title=United Arab Emirates International Religious Freedom Report |publisher=Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor |accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref>\n|label1 = [[Islam]]\n|value1 = 76\n|color1 = Green\n|label2 = [[Christianity]]\n|value2 = 12.6\n|color2 = DodgerBlue\n|label3 = [[Hinduism]]\n|value3 = 2\n|color3 = Orange\n|label4 = [[Buddhism]]\n|value4 = 2\n|color4 = Yellow\n|label5 = Other religions\n|value5 = 2.8\n|color5 = Chartreuse\n|label6 = [[Irreligion|No religion]]\n|value6 = 4\n|color6 = WhiteSmoke\n}}\n\n[[File:Jumeirah Mosque - panoramio (4).jpg|thumb|[[Jumeirah Mosque]] in [[Dubai]]. [[Islam]] is the official religion in the United Arab Emirates.]]\n[[Islam]] is both the official and majority religion in the [[United Arab Emirates]] followed by approximately 76% of the population.<ref name=\"The World Factbook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2122.html?countryName=Pakistan&countryCode=pk&regionCode=sas&#pk|title=The World Factbook|publisher=CIA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090617014724/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2122.html?countryName=Pakistan&countryCode=PK&regionCode=sas&#pk|archive-date=2009-06-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Al Nahayan]] and [[Al Maktoum]] ruling families adhere to [[Sunni Islam]] of [[Maliki]] school of [[jurisprudence]]. Many followers of the [[Hanbali]] school of [[Sunni Islam]] are found in [[Emirate of Sharjah|Sharjah]], [[Umm al-Quwain]], [[Ras al-Khaimah]] and [[Ajman]].<ref>Barry Rubin (2009), Guide to Islamist Movements, Volume 2, ME Sharpe, {{ISBN|978-0765617477}}, p. 310</ref> Their followers include the [[Al Qasimi]] ruling family.  Other religions represented in the country including [[Christianity]], [[Hinduism]], [[Buddhism]], [[Judaism]] and [[Sikhism]] are practiced by non-nationals.<ref name=\"irf127360\">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2009/127360.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091031224349/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2009/127360.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-10-31 |title=United Arab Emirates |publisher=State.gov |access-date=2010-11-24}}</ref>\n\n== Islam ==\n{{Main article|Islam in the United Arab Emirates}} \n{{See also|Shia Islam in the United Arab Emirates}}\nThere are more [[Sunni]] than [[Shiite]] Muslims among the residents. There are also a smaller number of [[Ismaili]] [[Shias]] and [[Ahmadiyya|Ahmadi]] Muslims.<ref name=\"The World Factbook\"/> The UAE's judicial system is derived from the [[civil law system]] and [[Sharia law]]. The court system consists of civil courts and [[Sharia|Sharia courts]]. According to [[Human Rights Watch]], UAE's criminal and civil courts apply elements of Sharia law, codified into its criminal code and family law, in a way which discriminates [[Women in the United Arab Emirates|against women]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/expat/expatnews/11012631/Human-Rights-Watch-warns-expat-women-about-the-UAE.html|title=Human Rights Watch warns expat women about the UAE}}</ref>\n\nSharia courts in the UAE have a significant amount of authority. [[Flogging]] is a punishment for criminal offences such as adultery, premarital sex and alcohol consumption.<ref name=bergner>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NqIkQz68_fgC&pg=PA2203|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices for 2008|work=Jeffrey T. Bergner|page=2203}}</ref><ref name=\"flog\">{{cite web |url=http://fanack.com/en/countries/uae/administration-politics/torture-and-flogging/ |title=Torture and flogging |work=Fanack |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809185136/http://fanack.com/en/countries/uae/administration-politics/torture-and-flogging/ |archive-date=9 August 2014 |url-status=dead |quote=UAE Sharia courts sentence to flogging persons found guilty of drug use, adultery, and prostitution in all emirates except Dubai.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightsvoices.org/EYEontheUN/un_101/figures/?p=2484|title=U.N. Commission on Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice: United Arab Emirates|work=Human Rights Voices}}</ref> Due to Sharia courts, flogging is legal with sentences ranging from 80 to 200 lashes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.kw/books?id=O5rs8UkMj64C&pg=PA2092|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices for 2007|page=2092}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corpun.com/counaej.htm|title=UAE: Judicial corporal punishment by flogging|work=World Corporal Punishment Research}}</ref> Between 2007 and 2013, many people in the UAE were sentenced to 100 lashes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://7daysindubai.com/news-14918/|title=Pregnant maid to get 100 lashes after being found guilty of illegal affair|date=9 October 2013|publisher=7daysindubai.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006151535/http://7daysindubai.com/news-14918/|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/NewsDetails.aspx?storyid=281982|work=Gulf Daily News|title=Teenager to be lashed for adultery}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/illicit-lovers-sentenced-to-100-lashes-each-1.712261|title=Illicit lovers sentenced to 100 lashes each|date=15 November 2010|work=Gulf News}}</ref><ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/nation/inside.asp?xfile=/data/courtroundup/2013/September/courtroundup_September33.xml&section=courtroundup|title=Two women sentenced to death for adultery|date=25 September 2013|work=Khaleej Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/courts/prison-for-couple-who-conceived-outside-of-wedlock|title=Prison for couple who conceived outside of wedlock|quote=KA, 19, Emirati, was sentenced to six months in prison. Her would-be husband, AM, Omani, was sentenced to 100 lashes and one year in prison.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/adulterer-to-be-lashed-jailed-in-sharjah-1.624274|title=Adulterer to be lashed, jailed in Sharjah|date=9 May 2010|work=Gulf News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/region/uae/report-2007|title=UAE \u2013 Amnesty International 2007|quote=In June, in the Emirate of Fujairah, a Shari'a (Islamic) court imposed a sentence of death by stoning on Shahin 'Abdul Rahman, a Bangladeshi national, after convicting him of adultery with Asma Bikham Bijam, a migrant domestic worker, who was sentenced to receive a flogging of 100 lashes and to be imprisoned for one year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/babylonbeyond/2010/06/the-court-in-abu-dhabi-ruled-today-that-the-18-year-old-emirati-woman-who-accused-six-men-of-gang-rape-will-serve-a-one-year.html|title=DUBAI: Alleged victim of gang rape sentenced to one year in prison|quote= At that point, she was facing a penalty for extramarital sex, which is 100 lashes and a minimum of three years in prison.}}</ref> Several Muslims in Abu Dhabi and Ajman were sentenced to 80 lashes for alcohol consumption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/man-to-get-80-lashes-for-drinking-alcohol-1.585233|title=Man to get 80 lashes for drinking alcohol in Ajman|date=19 February 2010|work=Gulf News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/courts/man-appeals-80-lashes-for-drinking-alcohol-in-abu-dhabi|title=Man appeals 80 lashes for drinking alcohol in Abu Dhabi|date=9 August 2012|work=The National}}</ref> An Estonian soldier in 2006 was sentenced to 40 lashes for being drunk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/estonian-soldier-to-be-lashed-1.233170|title=Estonian soldier to be lashed|last=Al Jandaly|first=Bassma|date=16 April 2006|work=Gulf News}}</ref> Several people have been sentenced to 60 lashes for illicit sex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/girl-to-receive-60-lashes-for-illicit-sex-1.185126|title=Girl to receive 60 lashes for illicit sex|date=20 June 2007|work=Gulf News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?xfile=data/theuae/2006/July/theuae_July99.xml&section=theuae&col=|title=Two sex workers are sentenced to lashes|date=3 July 2006|work=Khaleej Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/news/fullstory.php?newsid=11353|title=Indian lover in UAE sentenced to 60 lashes}}</ref> Sharia courts have penalized domestic workers with floggings.<ref name=\"drm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/zh-hans/node/129797/section/10|title=VI. Charges and Penalties against Domestic Workers|publisher=Human Rights Watch|year=2014}}</ref> Under UAE law, premarital sex is punishable by 100 lashes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/woman-denies-affair-after-hearing-she-faces-stoning|title=Woman denies affair after hearing she faces stoning|quote=Under the same law, premarital sex is punishable by 100 lashes.}}</ref>\n[[File:Iranian Shia Mosque, Dubai, UAE (4324609002).jpg|thumb|Shia Mosque in Dubai.]]\n[[Stoning]] is a legal punishment in the UAE. In 2006, an [[Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates|expatriate]] was sentenced to death by stoning for committing adultery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/MDE25/005/2006/en|title=UAE: Death by stoning/ flogging|publisher=Amnesty International}}</ref> Between 2009 and 2013, several people were sentenced to death by stoning.<ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-man-faces-stoning-in-uae-for-incest-1090813|title=Man faces stoning in UAE for incest}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/woman-denies-affair-after-hearing-she-faces-stoning|title=Woman denies affair after hearing she faces stoning|date=29 July 2009|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref> In May 2014, an Asian housemaid was sentenced to death by stoning in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://7daysindubai.com/expat-faces-death-stoning-admitting-court-cheating-husband/|title=Expat faces death by stoning after admitting in court to cheating on husband|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006154624/http://7daysindubai.com/expat-faces-death-stoning-admitting-court-cheating-husband/|archivedate=2014-10-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://emirateswoman.com/2014/05/05/woman-sentenced-death-stoning-abu-dhabi/|title=Woman Sentenced to Death by Stoning in UAE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatarliving.com/news/posts/asian-housemaid-gets-death-adultery-abu-dhabi|title=Asian housemaid gets death for adultery in Abu Dhabi}}</ref>\n\nSharia law dictates the [[Family law|personal status law]], which regulate matters such as marriage, divorce and child custody. The Sharia-based personal status law is applied to Muslims and sometimes non-Muslims.<ref name=\"lia\" /> Non-Muslim expatriates can be liable to Sharia rulings on marriage, divorce and child custody.<ref name=\"lia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-28638553|title=Britons 'liable to Sharia divorces' in UAE|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Sharia courts have exclusive jurisdiction over family law cases and also have jurisdiction over some criminal cases including adultery, premarital sex, robbery and related crimes.\n\n[[Apostasy]] is a crime [[punishable by death]] in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/12/10/us-religion-atheists-idUSBRE9B900G20131210|title=Atheists face death in 13 countries, global discrimination: study}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://beaveronline.co.uk/the-international-briefing-persecution-of-atheists-and-apostates/|title=The International Briefing: Persecution of Atheists and Apostates|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428131415/http://beaveronline.co.uk/the-international-briefing-persecution-of-atheists-and-apostates/|archivedate=2015-04-28}}</ref> UAE incorporates [[hudud]] crimes of Sharia into its Penal Code \u2013 apostasy being one of them.<ref name=\"shar\">{{cite journal|author=Butti Sultan Butti Ali Al-Muhairi |year=1996|jstor=3381546 |title=The Islamisation of Laws in the UAE: The Case of the Penal Code|journal=Arab Law Quarterly|volume=11|issue=4 |pages=350\u2013371}}</ref> Article 1 and Article 66 of UAE's Penal Code requires hudud crimes to be punished with the death penalty,<ref name=\"shar\" /><ref>Al-Muhairi (1997), Conclusion to the Series of Articles on the UAE Penal Law. Arab Law Quarterly, Vol. 12, No. 4</ref> therefore apostasy is punishable by death in the UAE.\n\nKissing in public is illegal and can result in [[deportation]].<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/public-kissing-can-lead-to-deportation |title=Public kissing can lead to deportation|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref> Expats in Dubai have been deported for kissing in public.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8602449.stm|title=Jailed Dubai kissing pair lose appeal over conviction}}</ref><ref name=\"gulfnews\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/women-get-jail-and-deportation-for-kissing-on-dubai-public-beach-1.106824 |title=Women get jail and deportation for kissing on Dubai public beach |work=Gulf News |date=25 May 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/10507147|title=London man tells of 'shock' jailing in Dubai over kiss}}</ref> In Abu Dhabi, people have been sentenced to jail followed by deportation for kissing in public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/courts/couple-deny-kissing-on-abu-dhabi-corniche?fb_action_ids=|title=Couple deny kissing on Abu Dhabi Corniche}}</ref> \n\n[[LGBT rights in the United Arab Emirates|Homosexuality]] is illegal: homosexuality is a [[capital offense]] in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arc-international.net/global-advocacy/universal-periodic-review/u/united-arab-emirates|title=United Arab Emirates|quote=Facts as drug trafficking, homosexual behaviour, and apostasy are liable to capital punishment.}}</ref><ref name=\"arc.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.care2.com/causes/man-accused-of-gay-handshake-stands-trial-in-dubai.html|title=Man Accused of 'Gay Handshake' Stands Trial in Dubai}}</ref> In 2013, an Emirati man was on trial for being accused of a \"gay handshake\".<ref name=\"arc.com\" /> Article 80 of the Abu Dhabi Penal Code makes sodomy punishable with imprisonment of up to 14 years, while article 177 of the Penal Code of Dubai imposes imprisonment of up to 10 years on consensual sodomy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glapn.org/sodomylaws/world/uae/united_arab_emirates.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060614053249/http://sodomylaws.org/world/uae/united_arab_emirates.htm |archive-date=14 June 2006 |title=Federal criminal statute In UAE |work=Sodomylaws.Org |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Amputation]] is a legal punishment in the UAE due to the Sharia courts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Amnesty International Report 1999 \u2013 United Arab Emirates|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6aa123b.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates: Briefing for the Human Rights Council Universal Periodic Review |url=http://lib.ohchr.org/HRBodies/UPR/Documents/Session15/AE/GIEACPCP_UPR_ARE_S15_2012_GloblaInitiativetoEndAllCorporalPunishmentofChildren_E.pdf|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates \u2013 Global Progress|url=http://www.endcorporalpunishment.org/pages/progress/reports/uae.html|quote=Punishments include flogging, amputation, and \u2013 as retaliation \u2013 injury similar to that for which the offender has been convicted of inflicting on the victim.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates \u2013 Country Reports on Human Rights Practices |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2000/nea/824.htm|quote=In February an Indonesian woman convicted of adultery by the Shari'a court in the Emirate of Fujairah, was sentenced to death by stoning after she purportedly insisted on such punishment.  The sentence was commuted on appeal to 1 year in prison, followed by deportation. In June 1998, the Shari'a court in Fujairah sentenced three Omani nationals convicted of robbery to have their right hands amputated. The Fujairah prosecutor's office instead commuted the sentence to a term of imprisonment.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Defining Sharia's role in the UAE's legal foundation|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/comment/defining-sharias-role-in-the-uaes-legal-foundation|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref> [[Crucifixion]] is a legal punishment in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/crucifixion-for-uae-murderers-1238085.html|title=Crucifixion for UAE murderers |work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/MDE25/011/1997/en|title=UAE: Further information on fear of imminent crucifixion and execution|publisher=Amnesty International|date=September 1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/MDE25/010/1997/en|title=UAE: Fear of imminent crucifixion and execution  |publisher=Amnesty International|date=September 1997}}</ref> Article 1 of the Federal Penal Code states that \"provisions of the [[Islamic Law]] shall apply to the crimes of doctrinal punishment, punitive punishment and blood money.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Federal Law No (3) of 1987 on Issuance of the Penal Code|url=https://www.unodc.org/tldb/showDocument.do?documentUid=6385&country=UAE|work=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525044622/https://www.unodc.org/tldb/showDocument.do?documentUid=6385&country=UAE|archivedate=2013-05-25}}</ref> The Federal Penal Code repealed only those provisions within the penal codes of individual emirates which are contradictory to the Federal Penal Code. Hence, both are enforceable simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web|title=Measures Against Corruptibility, Gifts and Gratification \u2013 Bribery in the Middle East|url=http://www.mafhoum.com/press2/brib76.pdf|work=Arab Law Quarterly}}</ref>\n\nDuring the month of [[Ramadan]], it is illegal to publicly eat, drink, or smoke between sunrise and sunset.<ref name=ramadan>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xs98Nv0Pe5E|title=Sharia law and Westerners in Dubai: should non-Muslims in UAE be made to face Islamic justice?}}</ref> Exceptions are made for pregnant women and children. The law applies to both Muslims and non-Muslims,<ref name=\"ramadan\" /> and failure to comply may result in arrest.<ref name=\"Riazat Butt\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/jul/31/dubai-tourists-must-respect-ramadan |title=Britons warned to respect Ramadan while holidaying in Dubai |author=Riazat Butt |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=31 July 2011 |location=London, UK|oclc=60623878 }}</ref> Dancing in public is illegal in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|title=Criminal Law of Dubai|url=http://www.lawyersuae.com/court-cases/criminal-law-of-dubai|publisher=lawyersuae.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dubai bans shisha tobacco smoking, dancing and holding hands|url=http://al-shorfa.com/en_GB/articles/meii/features/2009/03/20/feature-03|work=Al-Shorfa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=No dancing in public: Dubai|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/322024|work=Arab News}}</ref>\n\n== Christianity ==\n{{Main article|Christianity in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2015}}\n[[Protestantism in the United Arab Emirates|Protestants]] and [[Roman Catholicism in the United Arab Emirates|Roman Catholics]] form significant proportions of the Christian minority. The country has at least 33 churches.<ref name=\"irf127360\"/> The schools in public ownership have no Christian [[religious education]].<ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/gulf/uae-religion.htm |title=United Arab Emirates-Religion |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date=2006-04-17 |accessdate=2010-11-24}}</ref> Many Christians in the United Arab Emirates are of Asian, African, and [[Europe|European]] origin, along with Arabic speakers from Lebanon, Syria, and other countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refdag.nl/nieuws/groeiende_en_vitale_kerk_in_arabische_golf_1_494237 |title=Groeiende en vitale kerk in Arabische Golf - Nieuws - Reformatorisch Dagblad |publisher=Refdag.nl |date= |access-date=2010-11-24}}</ref>\n\n==Hinduism, Sikhism and Jainism==\n{{Main article|Hinduism in the United Arab Emirates|Sikhism in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2015}}\nHinduism and Jainism are practiced by a large percentage of the community of [[India]]ns and [[Sindhis|Sindhi]]s living in the UAE. To acknowledge the contribution of the Indian business community towards the early development of [[Dubai]] as a trade port, Sheikh [[Rashid bin Saeed Al Maktoum]] granted the permission and the land to build a [[Hindu Temple, Dubai|temple complex]] in [[Bur Dubai]]. There is also a Sikh temple south of Dubai, in [[Jebel Ali]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n==Buddhism==\n{{Main article|Buddhism in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2015}}\n\n==Judaism==\n{{Main article|History of the Jews in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nThere is a small [[Jews|Jewish]] community in the [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE). There is only one known [[synagogue]], in [[Dubai]], which has been open since 2008. The synagogue also welcomes visitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/for-the-first-time-dubais-jewish-community-steps-hesitantly-out-of-the-shadows/|title=For the first time, Dubai\u2019s Jewish community steps hesitantly out of the shadows|last=Herschlag|first=Miriam|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref> As of 2019, according to Rabbi [[Marc Schneier]], it is estimated that there are about 150 families to 3,000 Jews who live and worship freely in the UAE.<ref name=Ynt>{{cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5458305,00.html|title=The Jews of Dubai are on the map|publisher=ynetnews.com|date=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe synagogue in Dubai is supported by the UAE, with the appointment of a Minister for Tolerance in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.government.ae/en/about-the-uae/the-uae-government/government-of-future/tolerance-in-the-uae|title=Tolerance - The Official Portal of the UAE Government|website=www.government.ae|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref> The Ministry of Tolerance led to the creation of the National Tolerance Programme and official recognition of the Jewish community in the UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uaecabinet.ae/en/details/news/uae-cabinet-approves-national-tolerance-program|title=News|website=uaecabinet.ae|language=en|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\nAnother synagogue is planned to be built in Abu Dhabi, alongside a Mosque and a Church, as part of the Abrahamic Family House.<ref>https://www.gulfnews.com/amp/uae/government/abu-dhabi-a-synagoguemosque-and-church-will-be-in-one-location-1.1569067182292</ref>\n\n==Irreligion==\n{{Main article|Irreligion in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2015}}\nUp to 4% of people [[Irreligion by country|reported irreligious beliefs]] according to a Gallup poll. It is illegal for Muslims,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewire.com/global/2013/12/13-countries-where-atheism-punishable-death/355961/|title=There Are 13 Countries Where Atheism Is Punishable by Death|author=AbOhlheiser|date=|work=The Wire}}</ref> with [[apostates]] from Islam facing a maximum sentence of the [[Capital punishment in the United Arab Emirates|death penalty]] under [[Blasphemy law in the United Arab Emirates|the country's anti-blasphemy law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freethoughtreport.com/map/|title=Freedom of Thought Report - Map|author=|date=|work=freethoughtreport.com}}</ref> As such, there have been questions regarding [[freedom of religion in the United Arab Emirates]].\n\nAtheism in the region is mainly present among foreign [[Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates|expatriates]] and a very small number of local youth.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/comment/is-gulf-youth-increasingly-drawn-to-atheism|title=Is Gulf youth increasingly drawn to atheism?|work=The National|date=19 August 2012|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-bab.com/blog/2013/august/email-from-an-arab-atheist-2.htm|title=Email from an Arab atheist|work=Al-Bab|date=11 August 2013|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> According to [[Sultan Sooud Al-Qassemi]], due to Islam being founded in the [[Arabian Peninsula]] over 1,400 years ago, the [[Persian Gulf]] region enjoys a long Islamic history and tradition, and it is strongly associated with national identity; thus, any distancing or criticism of religion \"equates to distancing oneself from national identity\".<ref name=\"AM\"/> Al-Qassemi notes that the use of [[social media]] via the internet remains the strongest medium of expression for Gulf atheists, while providing anonymity; a pioneering Gulf blogger is the Emirati atheist Ahmed Ben Kerishan, who is known in the [[Blogging in Arab countries|Arabic blogosphere]] for advocating atheist and secular views.<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite news|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/03/gulf-atheism-uae-islam-religion.html|title=Gulf atheism in the age of social media|work=[[Al-Monitor]]|accessdate=11 July 2015|first=Sultan Sooud|last=Al-Qassemi|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710191405/http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/03/gulf-atheism-uae-islam-religion.html|archivedate=10 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jadaliyya.com/pages/index/3643/-pioneer-bloggers-in-the-gulf-arab-states|title=Pioneer Bloggers in the Gulf Arab States|work=Jadaliyya|date=20 December 2011|accessdate=11 July 2015|first=Sultan Sooud|last=Al-Qassemi}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Freedom of religion in the United Arab Emirates]]\n*[[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in the United Arab Emirates]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Religion in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Asia topic|Religion in}}\n\n[[Category:Religion in the United Arab Emirates]]\n", "text_old": "{{Pie chart\n|thumb = right\n|caption = Religion in the United Arab Emirates (2005 census)<ref name=religiousfreedom>{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2010/148850.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101123103428/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2010/148850.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2010-11-23|title=United Arab Emirates International Religious Freedom Report |publisher=Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights, and Labor |accessdate=2011-01-12}}</ref>\n|label1 = [[Islam]]\n|value1 = 72\n|color1 = Green\n|label2 = [[Christianity]]\n|value2 = 12.6\n|color2 = DodgerBlue\n|label3 = [[Hinduism]]\n|value3 = 2\n|color3 = Orange\n|label4 = [[Buddhism]]\n|value4 = 2\n|color4 = Yellow\n|label5 = Other religions\n|value5 = 2.8\n|color5 = Chartreuse\n|label6 = [[Irreligion|No religion]]\n|value6 = 4\n|color6 = WhiteSmoke\n}}\n\n[[File:Jumeirah Mosque - panoramio (4).jpg|thumb|[[Jumeirah Mosque]] in [[Dubai]]. [[Islam]] is the official religion in the United Arab Emirates.]]\n[[Islam]] is both the official and majority religion in the [[United Arab Emirates]] followed by approximately 76% of the population.<ref name=\"The World Factbook\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2122.html?countryName=Pakistan&countryCode=pk&regionCode=sas&#pk|title=The World Factbook|publisher=CIA|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090617014724/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2122.html?countryName=Pakistan&countryCode=PK&regionCode=sas&#pk|archive-date=2009-06-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> The [[Al Nahayan]] and [[Al Maktoum]] ruling families adhere to [[Sunni Islam]] of [[Maliki]] school of [[jurisprudence]]. Many followers of the [[Hanbali]] school of [[Sunni Islam]] are found in [[Emirate of Sharjah|Sharjah]], [[Umm al-Quwain]], [[Ras al-Khaimah]] and [[Ajman]].<ref>Barry Rubin (2009), Guide to Islamist Movements, Volume 2, ME Sharpe, {{ISBN|978-0765617477}}, p. 310</ref> Their followers include the [[Al Qasimi]] ruling family.  Other religions represented in the country including [[Christianity]], [[Hinduism]], [[Buddhism]], [[Judaism]] and [[Sikhism]] are practiced by non-nationals.<ref name=\"irf127360\">{{cite web|url=https://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2009/127360.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091031224349/http://www.state.gov/g/drl/rls/irf/2009/127360.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-10-31 |title=United Arab Emirates |publisher=State.gov |access-date=2010-11-24}}</ref>\n\n== Islam ==\n{{Main article|Islam in the United Arab Emirates}} \n{{See also|Shia Islam in the United Arab Emirates}}\nThere are more [[Sunni]] than [[Shiite]] Muslims among the residents. There are also a smaller number of [[Ismaili]] [[Shias]] and [[Ahmadiyya|Ahmadi]] Muslims.<ref name=\"The World Factbook\"/> The UAE's judicial system is derived from the [[civil law system]] and [[Sharia law]]. The court system consists of civil courts and [[Sharia|Sharia courts]]. According to [[Human Rights Watch]], UAE's criminal and civil courts apply elements of Sharia law, codified into its criminal code and family law, in a way which discriminates [[Women in the United Arab Emirates|against women]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/expat/expatnews/11012631/Human-Rights-Watch-warns-expat-women-about-the-UAE.html|title=Human Rights Watch warns expat women about the UAE}}</ref>\n\nSharia courts in the UAE have a significant amount of authority. [[Flogging]] is a punishment for criminal offences such as adultery, premarital sex and alcohol consumption.<ref name=bergner>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NqIkQz68_fgC&pg=PA2203|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices for 2008|work=Jeffrey T. Bergner|page=2203}}</ref><ref name=\"flog\">{{cite web |url=http://fanack.com/en/countries/uae/administration-politics/torture-and-flogging/ |title=Torture and flogging |work=Fanack |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809185136/http://fanack.com/en/countries/uae/administration-politics/torture-and-flogging/ |archive-date=9 August 2014 |url-status=dead |quote=UAE Sharia courts sentence to flogging persons found guilty of drug use, adultery, and prostitution in all emirates except Dubai.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.humanrightsvoices.org/EYEontheUN/un_101/figures/?p=2484|title=U.N. Commission on Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice: United Arab Emirates|work=Human Rights Voices}}</ref> Due to Sharia courts, flogging is legal with sentences ranging from 80 to 200 lashes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com.kw/books?id=O5rs8UkMj64C&pg=PA2092|title=Country Reports on Human Rights Practices for 2007|page=2092}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corpun.com/counaej.htm|title=UAE: Judicial corporal punishment by flogging|work=World Corporal Punishment Research}}</ref> Between 2007 and 2013, many people in the UAE were sentenced to 100 lashes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://7daysindubai.com/news-14918/|title=Pregnant maid to get 100 lashes after being found guilty of illegal affair|date=9 October 2013|publisher=7daysindubai.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006151535/http://7daysindubai.com/news-14918/|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gulf-daily-news.com/NewsDetails.aspx?storyid=281982|work=Gulf Daily News|title=Teenager to be lashed for adultery}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/illicit-lovers-sentenced-to-100-lashes-each-1.712261|title=Illicit lovers sentenced to 100 lashes each|date=15 November 2010|work=Gulf News}}</ref><ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/nation/inside.asp?xfile=/data/courtroundup/2013/September/courtroundup_September33.xml&section=courtroundup|title=Two women sentenced to death for adultery|date=25 September 2013|work=Khaleej Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/courts/prison-for-couple-who-conceived-outside-of-wedlock|title=Prison for couple who conceived outside of wedlock|quote=KA, 19, Emirati, was sentenced to six months in prison. Her would-be husband, AM, Omani, was sentenced to 100 lashes and one year in prison.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/adulterer-to-be-lashed-jailed-in-sharjah-1.624274|title=Adulterer to be lashed, jailed in Sharjah|date=9 May 2010|work=Gulf News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/region/uae/report-2007|title=UAE \u2013 Amnesty International 2007|quote=In June, in the Emirate of Fujairah, a Shari'a (Islamic) court imposed a sentence of death by stoning on Shahin 'Abdul Rahman, a Bangladeshi national, after convicting him of adultery with Asma Bikham Bijam, a migrant domestic worker, who was sentenced to receive a flogging of 100 lashes and to be imprisoned for one year.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/babylonbeyond/2010/06/the-court-in-abu-dhabi-ruled-today-that-the-18-year-old-emirati-woman-who-accused-six-men-of-gang-rape-will-serve-a-one-year.html|title=DUBAI: Alleged victim of gang rape sentenced to one year in prison|quote= At that point, she was facing a penalty for extramarital sex, which is 100 lashes and a minimum of three years in prison.}}</ref> Several Muslims in Abu Dhabi and Ajman were sentenced to 80 lashes for alcohol consumption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/man-to-get-80-lashes-for-drinking-alcohol-1.585233|title=Man to get 80 lashes for drinking alcohol in Ajman|date=19 February 2010|work=Gulf News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/courts/man-appeals-80-lashes-for-drinking-alcohol-in-abu-dhabi|title=Man appeals 80 lashes for drinking alcohol in Abu Dhabi|date=9 August 2012|work=The National}}</ref> An Estonian soldier in 2006 was sentenced to 40 lashes for being drunk.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/estonian-soldier-to-be-lashed-1.233170|title=Estonian soldier to be lashed|last=Al Jandaly|first=Bassma|date=16 April 2006|work=Gulf News}}</ref> Several people have been sentenced to 60 lashes for illicit sex.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/girl-to-receive-60-lashes-for-illicit-sex-1.185126|title=Girl to receive 60 lashes for illicit sex|date=20 June 2007|work=Gulf News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/DisplayArticleNew.asp?xfile=data/theuae/2006/July/theuae_July99.xml&section=theuae&col=|title=Two sex workers are sentenced to lashes|date=3 July 2006|work=Khaleej Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://expressindia.indianexpress.com/news/fullstory.php?newsid=11353|title=Indian lover in UAE sentenced to 60 lashes}}</ref> Sharia courts have penalized domestic workers with floggings.<ref name=\"drm\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/zh-hans/node/129797/section/10|title=VI. Charges and Penalties against Domestic Workers|publisher=Human Rights Watch|year=2014}}</ref> Under UAE law, premarital sex is punishable by 100 lashes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/woman-denies-affair-after-hearing-she-faces-stoning|title=Woman denies affair after hearing she faces stoning|quote=Under the same law, premarital sex is punishable by 100 lashes.}}</ref>\n[[File:Iranian Shia Mosque, Dubai, UAE (4324609002).jpg|thumb|Shia Mosque in Dubai.]]\n[[Stoning]] is a legal punishment in the UAE. In 2006, an [[Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates|expatriate]] was sentenced to death by stoning for committing adultery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/MDE25/005/2006/en|title=UAE: Death by stoning/ flogging|publisher=Amnesty International}}</ref> Between 2009 and 2013, several people were sentenced to death by stoning.<ref name=\"khaleejtimes.com\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/world/report-man-faces-stoning-in-uae-for-incest-1090813|title=Man faces stoning in UAE for incest}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/woman-denies-affair-after-hearing-she-faces-stoning|title=Woman denies affair after hearing she faces stoning|date=29 July 2009|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref> In May 2014, an Asian housemaid was sentenced to death by stoning in Abu Dhabi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://7daysindubai.com/expat-faces-death-stoning-admitting-court-cheating-husband/|title=Expat faces death by stoning after admitting in court to cheating on husband|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006154624/http://7daysindubai.com/expat-faces-death-stoning-admitting-court-cheating-husband/|archivedate=2014-10-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://emirateswoman.com/2014/05/05/woman-sentenced-death-stoning-abu-dhabi/|title=Woman Sentenced to Death by Stoning in UAE}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qatarliving.com/news/posts/asian-housemaid-gets-death-adultery-abu-dhabi|title=Asian housemaid gets death for adultery in Abu Dhabi}}</ref>\n\nSharia law dictates the [[Family law|personal status law]], which regulate matters such as marriage, divorce and child custody. The Sharia-based personal status law is applied to Muslims and sometimes non-Muslims.<ref name=\"lia\" /> Non-Muslim expatriates can be liable to Sharia rulings on marriage, divorce and child custody.<ref name=\"lia\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-28638553|title=Britons 'liable to Sharia divorces' in UAE|publisher=BBC}}</ref> Sharia courts have exclusive jurisdiction over family law cases and also have jurisdiction over some criminal cases including adultery, premarital sex, robbery and related crimes.\n\n[[Apostasy]] is a crime [[punishable by death]] in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/12/10/us-religion-atheists-idUSBRE9B900G20131210|title=Atheists face death in 13 countries, global discrimination: study}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://beaveronline.co.uk/the-international-briefing-persecution-of-atheists-and-apostates/|title=The International Briefing: Persecution of Atheists and Apostates|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428131415/http://beaveronline.co.uk/the-international-briefing-persecution-of-atheists-and-apostates/|archivedate=2015-04-28}}</ref> UAE incorporates [[hudud]] crimes of Sharia into its Penal Code \u2013 apostasy being one of them.<ref name=\"shar\">{{cite journal|author=Butti Sultan Butti Ali Al-Muhairi |year=1996|jstor=3381546 |title=The Islamisation of Laws in the UAE: The Case of the Penal Code|journal=Arab Law Quarterly|volume=11|issue=4 |pages=350\u2013371}}</ref> Article 1 and Article 66 of UAE's Penal Code requires hudud crimes to be punished with the death penalty,<ref name=\"shar\" /><ref>Al-Muhairi (1997), Conclusion to the Series of Articles on the UAE Penal Law. Arab Law Quarterly, Vol. 12, No. 4</ref> therefore apostasy is punishable by death in the UAE.\n\nKissing in public is illegal and can result in [[deportation]].<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/public-kissing-can-lead-to-deportation |title=Public kissing can lead to deportation|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref> Expats in Dubai have been deported for kissing in public.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/8602449.stm|title=Jailed Dubai kissing pair lose appeal over conviction}}</ref><ref name=\"gulfnews\">{{cite web|url=http://gulfnews.com/news/gulf/uae/crime/women-get-jail-and-deportation-for-kissing-on-dubai-public-beach-1.106824 |title=Women get jail and deportation for kissing on Dubai public beach |work=Gulf News |date=25 May 2008 }}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/10507147|title=London man tells of 'shock' jailing in Dubai over kiss}}</ref> In Abu Dhabi, people have been sentenced to jail followed by deportation for kissing in public.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/news/uae-news/courts/couple-deny-kissing-on-abu-dhabi-corniche?fb_action_ids=|title=Couple deny kissing on Abu Dhabi Corniche}}</ref> \n\n[[LGBT rights in the United Arab Emirates|Homosexuality]] is illegal: homosexuality is a [[capital offense]] in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arc-international.net/global-advocacy/universal-periodic-review/u/united-arab-emirates|title=United Arab Emirates|quote=Facts as drug trafficking, homosexual behaviour, and apostasy are liable to capital punishment.}}</ref><ref name=\"arc.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.care2.com/causes/man-accused-of-gay-handshake-stands-trial-in-dubai.html|title=Man Accused of 'Gay Handshake' Stands Trial in Dubai}}</ref> In 2013, an Emirati man was on trial for being accused of a \"gay handshake\".<ref name=\"arc.com\" /> Article 80 of the Abu Dhabi Penal Code makes sodomy punishable with imprisonment of up to 14 years, while article 177 of the Penal Code of Dubai imposes imprisonment of up to 10 years on consensual sodomy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glapn.org/sodomylaws/world/uae/united_arab_emirates.htm |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060614053249/http://sodomylaws.org/world/uae/united_arab_emirates.htm |archive-date=14 June 2006 |title=Federal criminal statute In UAE |work=Sodomylaws.Org |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Amputation]] is a legal punishment in the UAE due to the Sharia courts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Amnesty International Report 1999 \u2013 United Arab Emirates|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/3ae6aa123b.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates: Briefing for the Human Rights Council Universal Periodic Review |url=http://lib.ohchr.org/HRBodies/UPR/Documents/Session15/AE/GIEACPCP_UPR_ARE_S15_2012_GloblaInitiativetoEndAllCorporalPunishmentofChildren_E.pdf|page=3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates \u2013 Global Progress|url=http://www.endcorporalpunishment.org/pages/progress/reports/uae.html|quote=Punishments include flogging, amputation, and \u2013 as retaliation \u2013 injury similar to that for which the offender has been convicted of inflicting on the victim.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=United Arab Emirates \u2013 Country Reports on Human Rights Practices |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/drl/rls/hrrpt/2000/nea/824.htm|quote=In February an Indonesian woman convicted of adultery by the Shari'a court in the Emirate of Fujairah, was sentenced to death by stoning after she purportedly insisted on such punishment.  The sentence was commuted on appeal to 1 year in prison, followed by deportation. In June 1998, the Shari'a court in Fujairah sentenced three Omani nationals convicted of robbery to have their right hands amputated. The Fujairah prosecutor's office instead commuted the sentence to a term of imprisonment.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Defining Sharia's role in the UAE's legal foundation|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/comment/defining-sharias-role-in-the-uaes-legal-foundation|work=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]]}}</ref> [[Crucifixion]] is a legal punishment in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/crucifixion-for-uae-murderers-1238085.html|title=Crucifixion for UAE murderers |work=[[The Independent]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/MDE25/011/1997/en|title=UAE: Further information on fear of imminent crucifixion and execution|publisher=Amnesty International|date=September 1997}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/library/info/MDE25/010/1997/en|title=UAE: Fear of imminent crucifixion and execution  |publisher=Amnesty International|date=September 1997}}</ref> Article 1 of the Federal Penal Code states that \"provisions of the [[Islamic Law]] shall apply to the crimes of doctrinal punishment, punitive punishment and blood money.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Federal Law No (3) of 1987 on Issuance of the Penal Code|url=https://www.unodc.org/tldb/showDocument.do?documentUid=6385&country=UAE|work=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525044622/https://www.unodc.org/tldb/showDocument.do?documentUid=6385&country=UAE|archivedate=2013-05-25}}</ref> The Federal Penal Code repealed only those provisions within the penal codes of individual emirates which are contradictory to the Federal Penal Code. Hence, both are enforceable simultaneously.<ref>{{cite web|title=Measures Against Corruptibility, Gifts and Gratification \u2013 Bribery in the Middle East|url=http://www.mafhoum.com/press2/brib76.pdf|work=Arab Law Quarterly}}</ref>\n\nDuring the month of [[Ramadan]], it is illegal to publicly eat, drink, or smoke between sunrise and sunset.<ref name=ramadan>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Xs98Nv0Pe5E|title=Sharia law and Westerners in Dubai: should non-Muslims in UAE be made to face Islamic justice?}}</ref> Exceptions are made for pregnant women and children. The law applies to both Muslims and non-Muslims,<ref name=\"ramadan\" /> and failure to comply may result in arrest.<ref name=\"Riazat Butt\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2011/jul/31/dubai-tourists-must-respect-ramadan |title=Britons warned to respect Ramadan while holidaying in Dubai |author=Riazat Butt |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=31 July 2011 |location=London, UK|oclc=60623878 }}</ref> Dancing in public is illegal in the UAE.<ref>{{cite web|title=Criminal Law of Dubai|url=http://www.lawyersuae.com/court-cases/criminal-law-of-dubai|publisher=lawyersuae.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dubai bans shisha tobacco smoking, dancing and holding hands|url=http://al-shorfa.com/en_GB/articles/meii/features/2009/03/20/feature-03|work=Al-Shorfa}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=No dancing in public: Dubai|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/322024|work=Arab News}}</ref>\n\n== Christianity ==\n{{Main article|Christianity in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2015}}\n[[Protestantism in the United Arab Emirates|Protestants]] and [[Roman Catholicism in the United Arab Emirates|Roman Catholics]] form significant proportions of the Christian minority. The country has at least 33 churches.<ref name=\"irf127360\"/> The schools in public ownership have no Christian [[religious education]].<ref>{{cite web|author=John Pike |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/gulf/uae-religion.htm |title=United Arab Emirates-Religion |publisher=Globalsecurity.org |date=2006-04-17 |accessdate=2010-11-24}}</ref> Many Christians in the United Arab Emirates are of Asian, African, and [[Europe|European]] origin, along with Arabic speakers from Lebanon, Syria, and other countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refdag.nl/nieuws/groeiende_en_vitale_kerk_in_arabische_golf_1_494237 |title=Groeiende en vitale kerk in Arabische Golf - Nieuws - Reformatorisch Dagblad |publisher=Refdag.nl |date= |access-date=2010-11-24}}</ref>\n\n==Hinduism, Sikhism and Jainism==\n{{Main article|Hinduism in the United Arab Emirates|Sikhism in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2015}}\nHinduism and Jainism are practiced by a large percentage of the community of [[India]]ns and [[Sindhis|Sindhi]]s living in the UAE. To acknowledge the contribution of the Indian business community towards the early development of [[Dubai]] as a trade port, Sheikh [[Rashid bin Saeed Al Maktoum]] granted the permission and the land to build a [[Hindu Temple, Dubai|temple complex]] in [[Bur Dubai]]. There is also a Sikh temple south of Dubai, in [[Jebel Ali]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}\n\n==Buddhism==\n{{Main article|Buddhism in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2015}}\n\n==Judaism==\n{{Main article|History of the Jews in the United Arab Emirates}}\n\nThere is a small [[Jews|Jewish]] community in the [[United Arab Emirates]] (UAE). There is only one known [[synagogue]], in [[Dubai]], which has been open since 2008. The synagogue also welcomes visitors.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/for-the-first-time-dubais-jewish-community-steps-hesitantly-out-of-the-shadows/|title=For the first time, Dubai\u2019s Jewish community steps hesitantly out of the shadows|last=Herschlag|first=Miriam|website=www.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref> As of 2019, according to Rabbi [[Marc Schneier]], it is estimated that there are about 150 families to 3,000 Jews who live and worship freely in the UAE.<ref name=Ynt>{{cite news|url=https://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-5458305,00.html|title=The Jews of Dubai are on the map|publisher=ynetnews.com|date=5 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe synagogue in Dubai is supported by the UAE, with the appointment of a Minister for Tolerance in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.government.ae/en/about-the-uae/the-uae-government/government-of-future/tolerance-in-the-uae|title=Tolerance - The Official Portal of the UAE Government|website=www.government.ae|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref> The Ministry of Tolerance led to the creation of the National Tolerance Programme and official recognition of the Jewish community in the UAE.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://uaecabinet.ae/en/details/news/uae-cabinet-approves-national-tolerance-program|title=News|website=uaecabinet.ae|language=en|access-date=2018-12-06}}</ref>\n\nAnother synagogue is planned to be built in Abu Dhabi, alongside a Mosque and a Church, as part of the Abrahamic Family House.<ref>https://www.gulfnews.com/amp/uae/government/abu-dhabi-a-synagoguemosque-and-church-will-be-in-one-location-1.1569067182292</ref>\n\n==Irreligion==\n{{Main article|Irreligion in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Expand section|date=September 2015}}\nUp to 4% of people [[Irreligion by country|reported irreligious beliefs]] according to a Gallup poll. It is illegal for Muslims,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thewire.com/global/2013/12/13-countries-where-atheism-punishable-death/355961/|title=There Are 13 Countries Where Atheism Is Punishable by Death|author=AbOhlheiser|date=|work=The Wire}}</ref> with [[apostates]] from Islam facing a maximum sentence of the [[Capital punishment in the United Arab Emirates|death penalty]] under [[Blasphemy law in the United Arab Emirates|the country's anti-blasphemy law]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://freethoughtreport.com/map/|title=Freedom of Thought Report - Map|author=|date=|work=freethoughtreport.com}}</ref> As such, there have been questions regarding [[freedom of religion in the United Arab Emirates]].\n\nAtheism in the region is mainly present among foreign [[Expatriates in the United Arab Emirates|expatriates]] and a very small number of local youth.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenational.ae/thenationalconversation/comment/is-gulf-youth-increasingly-drawn-to-atheism|title=Is Gulf youth increasingly drawn to atheism?|work=The National|date=19 August 2012|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al-bab.com/blog/2013/august/email-from-an-arab-atheist-2.htm|title=Email from an Arab atheist|work=Al-Bab|date=11 August 2013|accessdate=11 July 2015}}</ref> According to [[Sultan Sooud Al-Qassemi]], due to Islam being founded in the [[Arabian Peninsula]] over 1,400 years ago, the [[Persian Gulf]] region enjoys a long Islamic history and tradition, and it is strongly associated with national identity; thus, any distancing or criticism of religion \"equates to distancing oneself from national identity\".<ref name=\"AM\"/> Al-Qassemi notes that the use of [[social media]] via the internet remains the strongest medium of expression for Gulf atheists, while providing anonymity; a pioneering Gulf blogger is the Emirati atheist Ahmed Ben Kerishan, who is known in the [[Blogging in Arab countries|Arabic blogosphere]] for advocating atheist and secular views.<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite news|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/03/gulf-atheism-uae-islam-religion.html|title=Gulf atheism in the age of social media|work=[[Al-Monitor]]|accessdate=11 July 2015|first=Sultan Sooud|last=Al-Qassemi|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710191405/http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/03/gulf-atheism-uae-islam-religion.html|archivedate=10 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jadaliyya.com/pages/index/3643/-pioneer-bloggers-in-the-gulf-arab-states|title=Pioneer Bloggers in the Gulf Arab States|work=Jadaliyya|date=20 December 2011|accessdate=11 July 2015|first=Sultan Sooud|last=Al-Qassemi}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Freedom of religion in the United Arab Emirates]]\n*[[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith in the United Arab Emirates]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Religion in the United Arab Emirates}}\n{{Asia topic|Religion in}}\n\n[[Category:Religion in the United Arab Emirates]]\n", "name_user": "AbdullahAhmed134", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Religion_in_the_United_Arab_Emirates"}
